Process called "iban_char_to_value" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Maps an IBAN character to its mod-97 integer value. Digits '0'..'9'
    map to 0..9; uppercase letters 'A'..'Z' map to 10..35. Lowercase
    letters are normalized to uppercase before mapping.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Branch on ASCII ranges. Returns -1 for unmappable characters.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Branch-based; predictable for typical IBAN content.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope

    If ch is greater than or equal to 48:
        If ch is less than or equal to 57:
            Return ch minus 48
        End If
    End If
    If ch is greater than or equal to 65:
        If ch is less than or equal to 90:
            Let val be ch minus 65
            Return val plus 10
        End If
    End If
    If ch is greater than or equal to 97:
        If ch is less than or equal to 122:
            Let val be ch minus 97
            Return val plus 10
        End If
    End If
    Return 0 minus 1
End Process

Process called "iban_compute_mod97" takes raw as Integer, raw_len as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes the mod-97 checksum of an IBAN per ISO 13616-1:2020 Annex A.
    Algorithm: rearrange the IBAN so the first 4 characters move to the
    end, then convert each character to its numeric value (digits 0-9,
    letters 10-35), then compute the resulting number mod 97. A valid
    IBAN returns 1.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Iterate through the rearranged string, accumulating a running mod-97
    value: for each character with value v (1 or 2 digit string), the
    accumulator becomes (acc * 10 + d) mod 97 for each decimal digit of v.
    This streaming approach avoids needing arbitrary-precision arithmetic.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Linear in IBAN length; ~30-40 character ops total.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Returns -1 on invalid character. Pure.
    @End Security_Scope

    If raw is equal to 0:
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If
    If raw_len is less than IBAN_MIN_LENGTH:
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If
    If raw_len is greater than IBAN_MAX_LENGTH:
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If
    Let acc be 0
    Let cursor be 4
    Note: Process positions 4..raw_len-1, then positions 0..3.
    While cursor is less than raw_len:
        Let ch be StringCore.string_char_at(raw, cursor)
        Let v be iban_char_to_value(ch)
        If v is less than 0:
            Return 0 minus 1
        End If
        If v is less than 10:
            Set acc to (acc multiplied by 10) plus v
            Set acc to acc modulo by 97
        Otherwise:
            Let tens be v divided by 10
            Let units be v modulo by 10
            Set acc to (acc multiplied by 10) plus tens
            Set acc to acc modulo by 97
            Set acc to (acc multiplied by 10) plus units
            Set acc to acc modulo by 97
        End If
        Set cursor to cursor plus 1
    End While
    Set cursor to 0
    While cursor is less than 4:
        Let ch be StringCore.string_char_at(raw, cursor)
        Let v be iban_char_to_value(ch)
        If v is less than 0:
            Return 0 minus 1
        End If
        If v is less than 10:
            Set acc to (acc multiplied by 10) plus v
            Set acc to acc modulo by 97
        Otherwise:
            Let tens be v divided by 10
            Let units be v modulo by 10
            Set acc to (acc multiplied by 10) plus tens
            Set acc to acc modulo by 97
            Set acc to (acc multiplied by 10) plus units
            Set acc to acc modulo by 97
        End If
        Set cursor to cursor plus 1
    End While
    Return acc
End Process

Process called "iban_parse" takes raw as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Parses and validates an IBAN string. Allocates an IBAN record carrying
    the validation result and component offsets. The raw string is borrowed
    (not copied); callers must keep it alive for the record's lifetime.
    Spaces within the input are tolerated by upper layers; this primitive
    expects a NUL-terminated raw string with no spaces.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    1. Compute length via string_length.
    2. Range-check 15..34 (global SWIFT IBAN registry bounds).
    3. First two chars must be uppercase letters (country code).
    4. Next two chars must be digits (check digits).
    5. Per-country length enforcement: look up the exact mandated length
       in the SWIFT IBAN Registry via iban_country_expected_length.
       Reject unknown countries (return value -1) and length mismatches.
    6. Compute mod-97; record is valid iff result equals 1.
    7. Allocate record, populate fields.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One allocation + linear scan. Sub-microsecond.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Returns 0 on null input or on a country that is not in the SWIFT IBAN
    Registry. Returns 0 on length mismatch (per-country enforcement). The
    record contains a borrowed pointer to the input; do not free the input
    before iban_destroy.
    @End Security_Scope

    If raw is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let raw_len be StringCore.string_length(raw)
    If raw_len is less than IBAN_MIN_LENGTH:
        Return 0
    End If
    If raw_len is greater than IBAN_MAX_LENGTH:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let c0 be StringCore.string_char_at(raw, 0)
    Let c1 be StringCore.string_char_at(raw, 1)
    Let valid_country be 1
    If c0 is less than 65:
        Set valid_country to 0
    End If
    If c0 is greater than 90:
        Set valid_country to 0
    End If
    If c1 is less than 65:
        Set valid_country to 0
    End If
    If c1 is greater than 90:
        Set valid_country to 0
    End If
    If valid_country is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let country_packed be (c0 multiplied by 256) plus c1
    Let expected_len be iban_country_expected_length(country_packed)
    If expected_len is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If raw_len is not equal to expected_len:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let c2 be StringCore.string_char_at(raw, 2)
    Let c3 be StringCore.string_char_at(raw, 3)
    Let valid_check_digits be 1
    If c2 is less than 48:
        Set valid_check_digits to 0
    End If
    If c2 is greater than 57:
        Set valid_check_digits to 0
    End If
    If c3 is less than 48:
        Set valid_check_digits to 0
    End If
    If c3 is greater than 57:
        Set valid_check_digits to 0
    End If
    Let mod_result be iban_compute_mod97(raw, raw_len)
    Let valid be 0
    If valid_check_digits is equal to 1:
        If mod_result is equal to 1:
            Set valid to 1
        End If
    End If
    Let r be Layout.allocate(IBAN_RECORD_SIZE)
    If r is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    MemoryCore.memory_set_int64(r, IBAN_FIELD_LENGTH, raw_len)
    MemoryCore.memory_set_int64(r, IBAN_FIELD_VALID, valid)
    MemoryCore.memory_set_int64(r, IBAN_FIELD_RAW_PTR, raw)
    MemoryCore.memory_set_int64(r, IBAN_FIELD_COUNTRY_CODE, country_packed)
    Let cd_value be ((c2 minus 48) multiplied by 10) plus (c3 minus 48)
    MemoryCore.memory_set_int64(r, IBAN_FIELD_CHECK_DIGITS, cd_value)
    MemoryCore.memory_set_int64(r, IBAN_FIELD_BBAN_OFFSET, 4)
    MemoryCore.memory_set_int64(r, IBAN_FIELD_BBAN_LENGTH, raw_len minus 4)
    Return r
End Process

Process called "iban_is_valid" takes r as Integer returns Integer:
    If r is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return MemoryCore.memory_get_int64(r, IBAN_FIELD_VALID)
End Process

